;; ============================================================
;; GAPS surfaced by trying to express this in Form
;; ============================================================
;;
;; GAP-1: No struct / record / dict syntax. Every structured value
;;        composes through positional `list`. A task field's meaning
;;        comes from position, not name. Surface for keyword args /
;;        named fields would help: `(task :id 19 :subject "..." ...)`
;;        — already gestured at in form-stdlib examples; needs to land
;;        in the parser.
;;
;; GAP-2: No date literal. "2026-05-20" is a string trivial, not a
;;        first-class date. A `DATE` format-recipe (in BAtomic) would
;;        make dates queryable by ordering, range, etc.
;;
;; GAP-3: No NodeID-of-cell references at the surface. Tasks here
;;        reference other tasks by integer id (4, 6, etc.) rather
;;        than by NodeID. Real substrate-resident tasks would
;;        carry NodeID children via cell-references — surface for
;;        `@task(4)` would help.
;;
;; GAP-4: List-of-strings positional binding is fragile. (task 1
;;        "subject" "status" (list) (list) "scope") relies on
;;        argument position; an ergonomic structured-record syntax
;;        would prevent silent field-order bugs.
;;
;; GAP-5: No formal "enum" for status. Values "pending", "in_progress",
;;        "completed" are bare strings; would benefit from an
;;        INDUCTIVE type (Status := Pending | InProgress | Completed)
;;        — now feasible with #21 done.
;;
;; GAP-6: Comments are read by the parser but not preserved as
;;        substrate cells. A real "decision log" in Form would want
;;        comments-as-cells so reasoning is queryable.
;;
;; GAP-7: No surface for "this is a snapshot at time T". The whole
;;        file is one big DO block; there's no temporal layer. Would
;;        benefit from a snapshot-recipe shape that carries the
;;        timestamp + frozen state.
;;
;; What it teaches: Form CAN express this state — the values intern
;; cleanly, the structure round-trips through walker — but the
;; surface ergonomics are still S-expression-positional. The
;; substrate-resident-grammar machinery is in place; what's needed
;; is more grammar cells (struct literal, keyword args, NodeID
;; references) to make this kind of artifact pleasant to write.
;;
;; These gaps would all be addressed by tasks already in the queue:
;; #15-18 (language ingestion/emission) provide the syntax-surface
;; machinery; #21 (INDUCTIVE, done) lets us define Status as an
;; algebraic datatype; the QUOTIENT (#19, done) lets us canonicalize
;; tasks-by-shape.
;;
;; Dogfooding worked: trying to use Form for this artifact surfaced
;; seven concrete improvements that turn into substrate writes once
;; the body grows them.
